f: \mathbb{R} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}
\lim_{x \to \infty}f'(x)=1
a \in \mathbb{R}
 \lim_{x \to \infty} \frac{e^{f(x+a)}}{e^{f(x)}} 
 \begin{align} \lim_{x \to \infty} \frac{e^{f(x+a)}}{e^{f(x)}}&=\lim_{n \to \infty}e^{f(x+a)}e^{-f(x)} \\ &=\lim_{x \to \infty}e^{f(x+a)-f(x)} \\ &=\lim_{x \to \infty}\left(e^{f(x+a)-f(x)}\right)^\frac{a}{a} \\ &=\lim_{x \to \infty}\left(e^\frac{f(x+a)-f(x)}{a}\right)^a \\ &=\left(e^{\lim_{x \to \infty}\frac{f(x+a)-f(x)}{a}}\right)^a \\ &=\left(e^{\lim_{x \to \infty}f'(x)}\right)^a \\ &=(e^1)^a\\ &=e^a \end{align} 
L=\lim\limits_{x\to \infty}f'(x)
\epsilon >0
N
x\ge N\implies |f'(x)-L|<\epsilon
x\ge n
\lim\limits_{x\to\infty}\frac{f(x+a)-f(x)}{a}=L
 \frac{f(x+a)-f(x)}{a}\ne f'(x)
\begin{align} \left|\frac{f(x+a)-f(x)}{a}-L\right| &=\left|\frac{1}{a}\int_x^{x+a}(f'(t)-L)dt\right|\\ &\le \frac{1}{a}\int_{x}^{x+a}|f'(t)-L|dt\\ &\le \frac1a\int_x^{x+a}\epsilon = \epsilon \end{align}
